title: For Sale:  AK-47 Polish Radom "Hellpup" Pistol
postcontent: For sale is a brand new, never fired, Polish AK-47 "Hellpup" pistol. This variant is no longer imported into the USA with the original classic bakelite-style furniture. When you do see them for sale, they now use black polymer furniture. The supply of these high-quality AK-47's from Radom in Poland has diminished substantially as the Radom factory now has multi-year government contracts to fulfill, limiting the number and range of products they can offer to the civilian market.This AK-47 pistol has a 9.25" barrel with a classic Krinkov-style flash hider on the end. The 7.62x39mm round is ideal for short barrels as the velocity lost at that barrel length is substantially less than lost by smaller calibers such as .223 (5.56x45mm) at the same length. It is perfect for turning into a short-barreled rifle (SBR) with a stock, or adding a pistol arm brace to avoid making an NFA item. Alternatively, one could attach a bungee sling and use it as is. This AK-47 was originally bought as it was the last import shipment that I knew would be coming with the original bakelite-style furniture. Selling to fund a custom bolt-action rifle project.Price is as pictured. I can throw in a standard steel milsurp 30-round magazine for an extra $20 if one is desired by the buyer. I am not interested in trades at this time.

title: For Sale:  Chinese Norinco SKS
postcontent:
For sale is an excellent condition Chinese Norinco SKS made at the Jianshe arsenal (arsenal 26) in 1966 (the year was determined by serial number from published lists online). The Chinese were known for making high quality SKS's. This SKS was imported pre-ban and had to have its bayonet removed on importation but the original sling was kept with it as well as the cleaning rod. The cleaning kit is also still in the buttstock. Replacement bayonets (they are not serial numbered) can be had online or at gun shows for $15-20. This rifle was never fired by the original purchaser nor myself. In fact, I removed some small residual cosmoline off of the rifle when I took ownership and cleaned the rifle with CLP.
This rifle was obtained in a multi-gun package purchase from the original buyer and collector who was selling off his collection in groups due to getting up there in years. This gentleman is the kind of collector who takes care of but never shoots his collection so I know it was in good hands.
As the rifle is in significantly better condition than the only other ones I can find for sale online at J&G (which have beat up metal and wood with bayonet but without sling), the price is set at $400. If you need ammo, I also have plentiful boxes of steel cased 123 grain FMJ ammo for $5 a box of 20.
At this time, I am not interested in trades.
